So, in the taxi companies of Budapest, a large proportion of cars was Lada, and the operation of these cars in intensive mode turned out to be the most effective [47]. The all-wheel drive Niva, which at that time had no analogues in its segment at that time, was very popular. exceeded supply and was supported by the emergence of a number of tuning versions offered by local dealers in the economically developed countries of the world. In addition to everyday operation in urban conditions, the Niva was widely used abroad as a vehicle for rangers, doctors, farmers, salesmen and policemen. In the middle of 1980 th foreign markets positively met the upgraded family of rear-wheel drive models Lada 2105/2107/2104.